
👽 test linux/amd64

Apply the changes required to reach the desired state of the configuration.

This will prompt for confirmation before making changes unless -auto-approve is used.

For complete Terraform/OpenTofu documentation, see:
https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/apply
https://opentofu.org/docs/cli/commands/apply

USAGE


    $ atmos terraform apply [flags]


EXAMPLES


    – Apply changes to a terraform component


     $ atmos terraform apply <component-name> -s <stack-name>


FLAGS

      --affected                           Apply the affected components in dependency order

      --all                                Apply all components in all stacks

      --auto-generate-backend-file string  Override auto_generate_backend_file setting from atmos.yaml (true/false)

      --ci                                 Enable CI mode for automated pipelines (writes job summary, outputs)

      --failure-mode string                Terraform apply failure handling mode. Supported values: fail-fast, keep-
                                           going (default fail-fast)

      --from-plan string                   Apply from plan file (uses deterministic location if path not specified)

  -h, --help                               help for apply

      --init-run-reconfigure string        Override init_run_reconfigure setting from atmos.yaml (true/false)

      --log-order string                   Order concurrent Terraform apply logs. Supported values: stream, grouped
                                           (default stream)

      --max-concurrency int                Maximum number of Terraform apply components to execute concurrently
                                           (default 1)

      --planfile string                    Set the plan file to use


COMPATIBILITY FLAGS

  These flags are passed through to the underlying terraform/tofu command.

      -auto-approve      Skip interactive approval of plan before applying
      -backup            Path to backup the existing state file
      -compact-warnings  Show warnings in a more compact form
      -destroy           Destroy all remote objects managed by the configuration
      -input             Ask for input for variables if not directly set (default: true)
      -json              Output apply results in JSON format
      -lock              Lock the state file when locking is supported (default: true)
      -lock-timeout      Duration to retry a state lock (default: 0s)
      -no-color          Disable color output in the command output
      -parallelism       Limit the number of concurrent operations (default: 10)
      -refresh           Update state prior to checking for differences (default: true)
      -refresh-only      Update state only, no resource changes
      -replace           Force replacement of a particular resource instance
      -state             Path to read and save state
      -state-out         Path to write updated state
      -target            Target specific resources for planning/applying
      -var               Set a value for one of the input variables
      -var-file          Load variable values from the given file


Use --help=usage for examples or --help=all for all flags and full help.
